19:06.060 --> 19:09.040
- I love Gerry,
and he's a good psychologist,

19:09.040 --> 19:11.110
but if he can't connect
with patients--

19:11.110 --> 19:13.050
- What evidence do you have
that he can't?

19:13.050 --> 19:14.050
- Look--

19:14.050 --> 19:15.110
- Have his patients left him

19:15.110 --> 19:16.190
since he established
this condition?

19:16.190 --> 19:17.230
- Some have.
- But most haven't.

19:17.230 --> 19:19.120
- The problem is,

19:19.120 --> 19:22.220
I need doctors
who can help build our clinic.

19:22.220 --> 19:25.010
He's unable to bring in
new business.

19:25.010 --> 19:26.150
- You've effectively
discharged him

19:26.150 --> 19:28.070
for a medical condition.

19:28.070 --> 19:30.070
- No, the discharge
was predicated

19:30.070 --> 19:33.120
on the inability to perform
the functions of the job.

19:34.230 --> 19:36.120
- What if he wears dark glasses?

19:36.120 --> 19:37.220
- How would you feel
about a therapist

19:37.220 --> 19:40.030
where you can't even
see his eyes?

19:40.030 --> 19:42.010
- I'd deal with it.

19:42.010 --> 19:45.110
- Look, part of the job
is cultivating new clientele.

19:45.110 --> 19:46.200
Gerry is unable to do this.

19:46.200 --> 19:48.100
Look, I like the guy.

19:48.100 --> 19:50.140
I wouldn't do this
if I didn't have to.

19:53.190 --> 19:56.000
- I'd seen Lynette Hayes around,

19:56.000 --> 19:58.180
and I'd always
wanted to meet her.

19:58.180 --> 20:00.010
I saw her
walking across the street

20:00.010 --> 20:02.150
looking into some store window.

20:02.150 --> 20:05.010
- What did you do?

20:05.010 --> 20:06.210
- I thought, "What the hell,"

20:06.210 --> 20:09.230
so I crossed over,
and I went to say hello.

20:09.230 --> 20:11.060
- And what happened?

20:11.060 --> 20:12.220
- I kind of put
a light hit on her.

20:12.220 --> 20:16.020
She seemed receptive,
so we just started talking.

20:16.020 --> 20:17.200
- How long
were the two of you

20:17.200 --> 20:21.000
talking out there on the street?

20:21.000 --> 20:22.040
- A few minutes.

20:22.040 --> 20:24.110
Then we started walking.

20:24.110 --> 20:26.010
We got to where she was parked,

20:26.010 --> 20:28.110
and then we were just
leaning against her car

20:28.110 --> 20:31.140
talking some more.

20:31.140 --> 20:33.100
- Did the two of you
get inside the car?

20:33.100 --> 20:34.210
- Yeah.

20:34.210 --> 20:37.060
We were getting
kind of cold standing outside.

20:37.060 --> 20:40.010
She asked me,
did I want to get in?

20:40.010 --> 20:42.210
- What happened once
the two of you were in the car?

20:42.210 --> 20:44.000
- She ran the heater
for a while,

20:44.000 --> 20:46.030
and we listened to some music.

20:46.030 --> 20:48.210
Then we fooled around.

20:48.210 --> 20:50.180
- So after just meeting you,

20:50.180 --> 20:54.030
she found you so irresistible
she just had to have you?

20:54.030 --> 20:55.180
- I guess so.

20:55.180 --> 20:57.230
- Then you made such
a favorable impression

20:57.230 --> 20:59.210
she just gave you her car?

20:59.210 --> 21:01.030
- No.

21:01.030 --> 21:03.040
She loaned it to me.

21:03.040 --> 21:04.230
I had lost track of time,

21:04.230 --> 21:07.040
and I was really late
for a job interview

21:07.040 --> 21:09.000
that I had across town.

21:09.000 --> 21:11.040
The job was really
important to me,

21:11.040 --> 21:13.150
and it was too late
for me to catch a bus.

21:13.150 --> 21:16.230
- So instead of offering
to drive you herself,

21:16.230 --> 21:19.210
she just gave her car
to a complete stranger?

21:19.210 --> 21:22.080
- Well, we weren't
total strangers at that point.

21:22.080 --> 21:25.210
And anyway, she had some things
she needed to get done,

21:25.210 --> 21:27.210
and so I was supposed to
meet her back there

21:27.210 --> 21:30.020
at that street at 5:00.

21:30.020 --> 21:32.120
- But you decided
to keep the car instead.

21:32.120 --> 21:36.170
- I got lost trying to find
the warehouse across town

21:36.170 --> 21:38.050
where I was supposed to
meet with this guy

21:38.050 --> 21:39.220
in shipping and receiving.

21:39.220 --> 21:43.040
Anyway, by the time I got back,
she was gone.

21:43.040 --> 21:46.180
- So you figured free car.
- No.

21:46.180 --> 21:50.180
I didn't have her phone number
or her last name.

21:50.180 --> 21:53.050
I was searching
for her registration,

21:53.050 --> 21:57.010
and that's when
the police arrested me.

21:57.010 --> 21:58.190
That's the truth.

22:09.080 --> 22:11.080
- Still love me?

22:11.080 --> 22:12.090
- She started it.

22:12.090 --> 22:13.160
I know that.

22:13.160 --> 22:16.080
- And she's not finished,
Eugene.

22:16.080 --> 22:19.080
Tomorrow morning,
you're on that stand.

22:19.080 --> 22:21.150
They'll be coming after you.

22:21.150 --> 22:22.190
- Yeah.

22:22.190 --> 22:25.080
- You can't lose control.

22:25.080 --> 22:27.210
You can't seem
erratic or volatile.

22:27.210 --> 22:30.150
You have to
remain calm in that chair.

22:30.150 --> 22:33.190
- It's a little easier
said than done.

22:33.190 --> 22:38.040
- You'll do it
because of the stakes.

22:38.040 --> 22:41.230
You'll do it.

22:41.230 --> 22:45.070
- I can't figure
how this happened.

22:45.070 --> 22:48.130
Custody battles,
divorce.

22:48.130 --> 22:50.050
I know how it can
turn into runaway hate,

22:50.050 --> 22:52.040
but Sharon and me?

22:52.040 --> 22:54.070
We get along.

22:54.070 --> 22:55.200
We still love each other.

22:55.200 --> 22:59.180
I know we both love Kendall.

23:02.120 --> 23:05.200
How'd this happen?

23:05.200 --> 23:13.180
<i>♪</i> ♪

23:18.140 --> 23:22.050
- What's up?

23:22.050 --> 23:25.020
- Well, I guess my radar.

23:25.020 --> 23:26.040
- What's going on?

23:26.040 --> 23:28.140
- Lynette, I could be way off,

23:28.140 --> 23:30.120
but I get a gut feeling
with witnesses,

23:30.120 --> 23:34.100
and after listening
to Randy Strunk's testimony,

23:34.100 --> 23:36.070
it had a believable ring to it.

23:36.070 --> 23:37.200
- You're not serious.

23:37.200 --> 23:39.000
- There's just
a couple of things

23:39.000 --> 23:41.030
that don't exactly make sense.

23:41.030 --> 23:42.130
After he took the car,

23:42.130 --> 23:44.080
he then returned
to the same area.

23:44.080 --> 23:46.080
He didn't change the plates.

23:46.080 --> 23:48.210
He acted like
an innocent person.

23:48.210 --> 23:52.000
- Why would I say
he just stole my car?

23:52.000 --> 23:53.140
- Is it possible
you thought he did

23:53.140 --> 23:55.090
when he didn't
come back soon enough?

23:55.090 --> 23:57.000
- No.

23:57.000 --> 23:59.160
He carjacked me.

24:02.040 --> 24:03.130
- Mr. and Mrs. Hayes,

24:03.130 --> 24:05.040
could you excuse us
for a second?

24:05.040 --> 24:07.130
I--
- Helen, what's this about?

24:07.130 --> 24:09.190
- I need to speak
with your daughter in private.

24:09.190 --> 24:11.000
Please.

24:27.120 --> 24:30.080
Lynette, if you are
making this up,

24:30.080 --> 24:32.010
a man is facing jail.

24:32.010 --> 24:34.090
- I'm not making this up.
- He carjacked you.

24:34.090 --> 24:37.190
- Yes.

24:37.190 --> 24:39.010
- Look, I know it was
your father

24:39.010 --> 24:40.150
who reported this to the police.

24:40.150 --> 24:43.030
Are you just sticking
to the story you gave him?

24:43.030 --> 24:45.030
- No.

24:45.030 --> 24:47.040
It's the truth.

24:52.220 --> 24:54.140
- If anything,
Kendall needs to spend

24:54.140 --> 24:56.230
more time with me,
not less.

24:56.230 --> 24:58.200
- How did Kendall
get those drugs?

24:58.200 --> 25:00.030
- He got them from someone

25:00.030 --> 25:02.110
who works for
a former client of mine.

25:02.110 --> 25:04.120
It was an unfortunate
coincidence.

25:04.120 --> 25:07.120
- Did you ever introduce Kendall
to this former client of yours?

25:07.120 --> 25:08.140
- Of course not.

25:08.140 --> 25:09.150
- Have you ever,
in any way,

25:09.150 --> 25:10.220
conveyed to Kendall

25:10.220 --> 25:12.160
that it was okay
to take or sell drugs?

25:12.160 --> 25:14.020
- No.

25:14.020 --> 25:15.090
- Why do you think
your ex-wife

25:15.090 --> 25:16.230
blames you
for Kendall's problems?

25:16.230 --> 25:19.040
- Sharon has always had
ideological problems

25:19.040 --> 25:20.150
with my job.

25:20.150 --> 25:22.080
I think when
this arrest happened,

25:22.080 --> 25:24.110
it hit a lot
of nerves and fears.

25:24.110 --> 25:25.200
I also think she blames

25:25.200 --> 25:27.200
the failure of our marriage
on my job,

25:27.200 --> 25:31.080
and she's reliving
a lot of that anger, I guess.

25:31.080 --> 25:32.230
- Can you understand that?

25:32.230 --> 25:34.200
- I can understand her fear.

25:34.200 --> 25:36.110
When Kendall got arrested,
I was afraid too.

25:36.110 --> 25:39.000
I also got angry.

25:39.000 --> 25:41.160
But I do not understand
her punishing me,

25:41.160 --> 25:45.020
and I certainly don't understand
her punishing Kendall,

25:45.020 --> 25:47.020
and that's what
you're doing, Sharon.

25:52.040 --> 25:54.100
- Your son got arrested
for possessing drugs,

25:54.100 --> 25:56.160
drugs that he bought
off of one of your clients.

25:56.160 --> 25:58.130
- That was a coincidence,
as I said.

25:58.130 --> 26:01.150
- Your lawyer, Ms. Frutt,
she was recently arrested

26:01.150 --> 26:03.170
on drug charges herself,
wasn't she?

26:03.170 --> 26:04.220
- Those charges were dismissed.

26:04.220 --> 26:06.180
She was set up by the police.

26:06.180 --> 26:08.020
- That's exactly
what Kendall said

26:08.020 --> 26:09.090
when you asked him
how the drugs

26:09.090 --> 26:10.210
ended up in his locker,
isn't it?

26:10.210 --> 26:12.210
- Except in Ellenor's case
it was true.

26:12.210 --> 26:15.020
- A client dropped a bag
of what was thought to be drugs

26:15.020 --> 26:16.030
on Ms. Frutt's desk.

26:16.030 --> 26:17.120
- That's right.

26:17.120 --> 26:19.060
- And when asked
who the drugs belonged to,

26:19.060 --> 26:22.130
Ms. Frutt responded,
"I don't know," didn't she?

26:22.130 --> 26:24.010
- Yes.
- But she knew

26:24.010 --> 26:26.050
where the drugs came from,
didn't she?

26:26.050 --> 26:27.050
- As lawyers,
we have a duty

26:27.050 --> 26:28.170
not to betray our clients.

26:28.170 --> 26:31.210
- So Ms. Frutt
did the right thing by lying?

26:31.210 --> 26:34.120
- In that context,
it wasn't lying.

26:34.120 --> 26:35.120
- It was telling the truth?

26:35.120 --> 26:36.140
- No.
- Which was it?

26:36.140 --> 26:37.180
- It was protecting our client,

26:37.180 --> 26:39.020
which,
as you well know,

26:39.020 --> 26:40.060
we have an ethical
obligation to do.

26:40.060 --> 26:41.080
- Yes.

26:41.080 --> 26:43.000
Did you sit down
and explain that

26:43.000 --> 26:44.050
to your son, Mr. Young?

26:44.050 --> 26:45.050
- Kendall knows
about our duties.

26:45.050 --> 26:46.150
We have these talks--

26:46.150 --> 26:48.000
- No, I'm not talking
in general.

26:48.000 --> 26:49.140
I'm referring to
that specific occasion

26:49.140 --> 26:52.140
after he witnessed Ellenor Frutt
lying to the police.

26:52.140 --> 26:55.030
Did you sit down and explain
the situation to him?

26:55.030 --> 26:56.220
- Not that time, no.

26:56.220 --> 26:58.080
- Can you honestly say
that you have

26:58.080 --> 27:00.090
taught Kendall
right from wrong,

27:00.090 --> 27:01.160
truth from lies?

27:01.160 --> 27:03.180
- I have never, ever
encouraged my son

27:03.180 --> 27:05.170
to break the law or to lie.

27:09.220 --> 27:11.180
- My dad says,
"If you get caught,

27:11.180 --> 27:13.220
"never admit to anything,
even to your lawyer,

27:13.220 --> 27:16.180
because they'll be stuck
with whatever you tell 'em."

27:22.150 --> 27:24.230
- I never told him that.

27:24.230 --> 27:26.130
- Is that the truth
or a justifiable lie?

27:26.130 --> 27:28.030
- Objection!

27:28.030 --> 27:29.210
- Kendall knows what I do
for a living, Mr. Tager.

27:29.210 --> 27:31.180
- Yes, in fact,
he spends a lot of time

27:31.180 --> 27:33.060
at your office, doesn't he?

27:33.060 --> 27:34.190
- Until this happened.

27:34.190 --> 27:36.120
- He was right there
when the police charged in

27:36.120 --> 27:38.230
with their guns
arresting Ellenor Frutt.

27:38.230 --> 27:41.030
He was even in the line of fire,
wasn't he?

27:41.030 --> 27:42.190
- You know that wasn't
a common occurrence.

27:42.190 --> 27:46.030
- On average,
how many waking hours a week

27:46.030 --> 27:48.140
do you spend with your son
outside the office?

27:48.140 --> 27:50.010
- I work a lot of hours.

27:50.010 --> 27:52.040
That's why he's with me at work.

27:52.040 --> 27:54.010
- And that's his exposure
to you, isn't it?

27:54.010 --> 27:55.070
Eugene Young, the lawyer.

27:55.070 --> 27:56.070
- And father.

27:56.070 --> 27:57.130
And father.

27:57.130 --> 27:59.020
- Father at work.

28:01.170 --> 28:03.010
Reference was made earlier
to plan B.

28:03.010 --> 28:04.030
What is that?

28:04.030 --> 28:05.160
- It's a defense strategy.

28:05.160 --> 28:07.190
- More specifically,
it means accusing someone

28:07.190 --> 28:10.040
in open court
of committing the crime.

28:10.040 --> 28:11.140
- Basically.

28:11.140 --> 28:13.110
- According to recent
court transcripts,

28:13.110 --> 28:14.190
you accused a brother
of beheading his sister

28:14.190 --> 28:16.050
even though you didn't believe

28:16.050 --> 28:18.050
that he was really
involved in the death.

28:18.050 --> 28:20.040
Correct?
- Yes.

28:20.040 --> 28:22.090
- Ever sit down
and talk to Kendall

28:22.090 --> 28:25.210
about why
you do these things in court?

28:25.210 --> 28:28.000
- Yes, I have.

28:28.000 --> 28:30.000
- Ever been booked
on assault, Mr. Young?

28:30.000 --> 28:31.210
- Once.
The charge was dropped.

28:31.210 --> 28:33.220
- Yeah, you got mad
at one of your clients

28:33.220 --> 28:35.080
who sodomized two young boys.

28:35.080 --> 28:36.200
You beat him up
in open court, right?

28:36.200 --> 28:37.200
- Objection!

28:37.200 --> 28:38.200
This has no relevance.

28:38.200 --> 28:40.020
- Everything is fair game.

28:40.020 --> 28:42.120
You made that clear.
- All right.

28:42.120 --> 28:46.080
I'll give you a little latitude,
Mr. Tager.

28:46.080 --> 28:49.080
- When this case was filed,
you were under court order

28:49.080 --> 28:51.110
not to discuss the merits of it
with your son Kendall.

28:51.110 --> 28:52.200
Is that right, sir?
- Yes.

28:52.200 --> 28:55.010
- You talk to him about it
two nights ago?

28:55.010 --> 28:57.010
- He was confused
as to what was going on.

28:57.010 --> 28:59.150
- You basically tell him
that his mother was wrong?

28:59.150 --> 29:03.050
- I told him we disagree
as to what was best.

29:03.050 --> 29:04.220
- Well, would it surprise you
if he went home

29:04.220 --> 29:06.220
with the idea
that you thought she was wrong?

29:06.220 --> 29:09.090
Night before the hearing,
you violate a court order,

29:09.090 --> 29:12.030
position your son
on your version of the merits.

29:15.000 --> 29:18.130
Are these the good footsteps
for a son to step in?

29:24.010 --> 29:26.110
- He's being fired
for a medical condition.

29:26.110 --> 29:27.150
That's contrary to law.

29:27.150 --> 29:29.000
- He's being terminated

29:29.000 --> 29:31.050
for an inability
to perform the functions--

29:31.050 --> 29:32.220
- Appearance is not a function.

29:32.220 --> 29:34.120
He has sixth nerve palsy

29:34.120 --> 29:36.060
brought about by head trauma,
and there's no--

29:36.060 --> 29:38.200
- Look, I don't know much
about psychology, Counsel,

29:38.200 --> 29:42.160
but I do suspect that if I were
to go see a therapist

29:42.160 --> 29:44.120
to unearth my troubles,

29:44.120 --> 29:47.160
it wouldn't help to have him
look back at me cross-eyed.

29:47.160 --> 29:49.130
- And that is bigotry.

29:49.130 --> 29:51.040
So he looks different.

29:51.040 --> 29:53.190
In time--
- Step up here, Mr. Pyle.

29:53.190 --> 29:57.040
Dr. Pyle.

29:57.040 --> 30:00.090
Okay, I'm looking
to get an idea.

30:00.090 --> 30:03.090
My mother-in-law
has got delirium.

30:03.090 --> 30:05.020
Tell us what that is.

30:05.020 --> 30:08.020
- Delirium is basically
a disturbance of consciousness.

30:08.020 --> 30:09.180
It can affect cognition,

30:09.180 --> 30:11.190
often manifested
by a reduced clarity

30:11.190 --> 30:13.120
of awareness of the environment.

30:13.120 --> 30:15.130
It can cause focus problems.

30:15.130 --> 30:18.010
Attention deficit problems
are common.

30:18.010 --> 30:21.200
The person is frequently
easily distracted

30:21.200 --> 30:24.040
by irrelevant stimuli,

30:24.040 --> 30:27.060
and it's often difficult
to engage

30:27.060 --> 30:30.020
in long, sustained
periods of conversation.

30:30.020 --> 30:32.030
There's also disorientation
as to time--

30:32.030 --> 30:33.050
- I'm sorry.

30:33.050 --> 30:34.100
I'm upholding the discharge.

30:34.100 --> 30:35.190
- Your Honor.

30:35.190 --> 30:37.230
- Ms. Washington,
this may not seem fair,

30:37.230 --> 30:40.080
but it's tough
to take him seriously.

30:40.080 --> 30:42.180
- You can't penalize him
for something he can't control.

30:42.180 --> 30:44.110
- Nor should I penalize them.

30:44.110 --> 30:47.230
Dr. Pyle,
you may be an excellent doctor,

30:47.230 --> 30:50.150
but medicine is business
these days too.

30:50.150 --> 30:52.050
And under the adage,

30:52.050 --> 30:55.080
"You only get one chance
to make a first impression,"

30:55.080 --> 30:57.180
I have to sympathize
with the defendant as well.

30:57.180 --> 30:59.000
- This isn't fair.

30:59.000 --> 31:00.050
- And your problem,
young lady,

31:00.050 --> 31:02.140
is that you think
justice is fair.

31:06.140 --> 31:08.090
- I'm not a big fan of ex parte.

31:08.090 --> 31:10.190
What's the mystery?

31:10.190 --> 31:12.190
- I'm not sure
I have good-faith belief

31:12.190 --> 31:14.190
in the defendant's
guilt anymore.

31:14.190 --> 31:17.050
- Why?

31:17.050 --> 31:19.150
- I guess it comes down
to credibility.

31:19.150 --> 31:22.010
My gut tells me
she fed her father this story,

31:22.010 --> 31:24.210
he insisted on the arrest,
and she's cornered.

31:24.210 --> 31:26.210
- What have you got
to support this?

31:26.210 --> 31:28.130
- Oh, just listening
to their testimony.

31:28.130 --> 31:30.140
I think I believe him.

31:30.140 --> 31:31.140
- So what?

31:31.140 --> 31:33.010
You're not the jury.

31:33.010 --> 31:34.010
- Still,
if a DA doesn't have

31:34.010 --> 31:35.130
a good-faith belief--

31:35.130 --> 31:37.040
- That may affect
your bringing the charges,

31:37.040 --> 31:38.190
but your weighing the testimony
is irrelevant.

31:38.190 --> 31:40.060
Come on.

31:40.060 --> 31:42.200
- And if I brought
a motion to dismiss?

31:42.200 --> 31:45.020
- Forget it.

31:45.020 --> 31:47.170
And don't tank
your closing, either.

31:47.170 --> 31:49.080
Defense attorneys
aren't the only ones

31:49.080 --> 31:51.140
with obligations
in that room.

31:59.230 --> 32:01.100
- Why'd you do this, Sharon?

32:01.100 --> 32:03.010
- Here you go,
disobeying another court order.

32:03.010 --> 32:05.180
We're not supposed
to talk about this outside.

32:11.050 --> 32:13.230
- Why'd you do this?

32:19.130 --> 32:21.220
- I know you love him.

32:24.030 --> 32:26.190
But I also know I'm losing him.

32:28.230 --> 32:32.200
If it were to you, Eugene,
I could deal with it,

32:32.200 --> 32:35.090
but I'm losing him
to something that--

32:38.190 --> 32:43.220
He's a good kid
becoming a bad kid.

32:43.220 --> 32:45.060
You don't see that,

32:45.060 --> 32:49.130
either because
you don't want to,

32:49.130 --> 32:51.180
or you can't.

32:58.030 --> 33:00.190
- Do you really
think he's better...

33:07.080 --> 33:09.160
Cut off from me?

33:12.000 --> 33:14.070
- Yes.

33:14.070 --> 33:17.070
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

33:17.070 --> 33:25.050
<i>♪</i> ♪

33:43.110 --> 33:45.050
- This isn't about
who's a better person

33:45.050 --> 33:46.230
or who loves Kendall more.

33:46.230 --> 33:49.150
It's what's
in the boy's best interests.

33:49.150 --> 33:52.040
We've listened
to the guardian ad litem,

33:52.040 --> 33:54.120
somebody who is neutral,
linking Kendall's problems

33:54.120 --> 33:56.190
to his contact with his father.

33:56.190 --> 34:00.150
A boy losing an ability
to distinguish right from wrong.

34:00.150 --> 34:02.160
We all saw that tape.

34:02.160 --> 34:04.140
An 11-year-old boy

34:04.140 --> 34:07.020
versed on the how-tos
of drug dealing.

34:07.020 --> 34:09.110
Who in this room
wasn't horrified?

34:09.110 --> 34:11.179
Eugene Young was sued
for intentional infliction

34:11.179 --> 34:14.040
of emotional distress when,
in open court,

34:14.040 --> 34:16.190
he accused a brother
of killing his own sister,

34:16.190 --> 34:21.010
an allegation he admittedly
didn't really believe.

34:21.010 --> 34:24.159
And in defense of Eugene Young,
his colleague, Jimmy Berluti,

34:24.159 --> 34:28.170
described him
as being in extreme denial,

34:28.170 --> 34:33.170
a man struggling to survive
what he does for a living.

34:33.170 --> 34:37.219
That struggle
is affecting Kendall.

34:37.219 --> 34:41.040
We're not asking for punishment,
or that it be permanent,

34:41.040 --> 34:44.070
but for now,

34:44.070 --> 34:46.110
we have to follow
Dr. Morrison's recommendation

34:46.110 --> 34:49.190
and appoint Sharon Young
as full custodian.

34:51.159 --> 34:54.120
In the end, it's not about
a mother or a father.

34:54.120 --> 34:58.030
It's about the welfare
of an 11-year-old boy

34:58.030 --> 35:02.050
who very clearly needs help.

35:08.000 --> 35:12.060
- We see young kids in this room
every day arrested for drugs.

35:12.060 --> 35:14.130
We don't take them
away from their parents.

35:14.130 --> 35:16.030
Just the opposite.

35:16.030 --> 35:19.030
The courts usually plead
for the parents to step in.

35:19.030 --> 35:21.210
That's exactly what Eugene Young
would like to do.

35:21.210 --> 35:26.010
This is a huge overreaction
to a bad event.

35:26.010 --> 35:27.110
There is nothing--

35:27.110 --> 35:31.080
nothing to even suggest
any parental unfitness.

35:31.080 --> 35:35.050
Mr. Tager quoted Jimmy Berluti's
closing argument as evidence.

35:35.050 --> 35:36.150
Well, he left out
the part of the summation

35:36.150 --> 35:39.110
where Mr. Berluti
referred to Eugene Young

35:39.110 --> 35:41.210
as deeply honorable,

35:41.210 --> 35:44.080
dignified,

35:44.080 --> 35:47.210
a hero.

35:47.210 --> 35:49.130
I second that.

35:54.070 --> 35:55.140
So do you, Sharon.

35:59.120 --> 36:02.030
There is nobody--

36:02.030 --> 36:03.170
nobody who's
walked through these doors

36:03.170 --> 36:05.230
with more honor,

36:05.230 --> 36:10.090
more dignity and morality,

36:10.090 --> 36:13.070
than the man sitting over there.

36:26.120 --> 36:27.190
- If you recant,
I promise,

36:27.190 --> 36:29.090
there will be
no perjury charges.

36:29.090 --> 36:30.230
- Why are you doing this?

36:30.230 --> 36:31.230
- Lynnette,
I'm just saying,

36:31.230 --> 36:33.200
if you did make this up--

36:33.200 --> 36:36.100
- It's bad enough
the defense attorney attacks me.

36:36.100 --> 36:39.190
Now the DA goes after me too?

36:39.190 --> 36:42.060
He carjacked me.

36:42.060 --> 36:44.140
He did.

36:48.230 --> 36:50.230
- Randy Strunk, well,
he's got to be

36:50.230 --> 36:52.130
the luckiest man in the world.

36:52.130 --> 36:55.070
He meets a very
attractive woman who,

36:55.070 --> 36:57.170
even though she's
a complete stranger,

36:57.170 --> 36:59.170
just can't help herself

36:59.170 --> 37:03.000
and agrees to fool around
with him in her car.

37:03.000 --> 37:07.000
Then, well, she generously
gifts him with her car.

37:08.100 --> 37:11.030
That happens every day,
doesn't it?

37:11.030 --> 37:14.040
Randy isn't lucky,
ladies and gentlemen.

37:14.040 --> 37:16.230
He's just careful.

37:16.230 --> 37:18.190
He chose his victim.

37:18.190 --> 37:20.120
He chose the time.

37:20.120 --> 37:24.100
He chose a location where
there would be no eyewitnesses.

37:24.100 --> 37:27.190
Randy chose every single detail
of the attack

37:27.190 --> 37:29.170
to work to his advantage,

37:29.170 --> 37:31.200
and after he got caught,

37:31.200 --> 37:35.000
he, along with his attorney,

37:35.000 --> 37:38.220
chose the strategy
of putting the victim on trial.

37:40.120 --> 37:44.000
He said, she said
equals reasonable doubt.

37:44.000 --> 37:47.090
Go ahead,
put him back out there.

37:47.090 --> 37:49.170
Just don't forget
to lock your car doors.

37:51.200 --> 37:55.030
- My definition
of the luckiest man in the world

37:55.030 --> 37:57.080
wouldn't be an innocent man
convicted for a crime

37:57.080 --> 37:58.180
he didn't do.

37:58.180 --> 38:00.090
Here's a flash.

38:00.090 --> 38:02.060
Sometimes the defendant

38:02.060 --> 38:06.080
actually is
the victim of false charges.

38:06.080 --> 38:10.090
Maybe she thought
he stood her up or duped her,

38:10.090 --> 38:14.110
or maybe wasn't really
coming back with her car.

38:14.110 --> 38:16.040
I don't know
what was in her mind

38:16.040 --> 38:19.080
when she told her father
what happened,

38:19.080 --> 38:21.170
but she wasn't carjacked.

38:21.170 --> 38:23.080
No bruises.

38:23.080 --> 38:27.060
No physical signs
of anything violent.

38:28.170 --> 38:31.190
She wasn't carjacked.

38:31.190 --> 38:34.100
This case reminds me
of a question

38:34.100 --> 38:36.000
we used to have
on tests in school

38:36.000 --> 38:37.230
when I was growing up.

38:37.230 --> 38:42.050
Orange, apple, pear, hammer.

38:42.050 --> 38:45.100
Which one doesn't fit?

38:45.100 --> 38:48.110
Here, according to
Lynnette Hayes,

38:48.110 --> 38:49.210
we have an attacker
with a knife

38:49.210 --> 38:51.110
who took her car,

38:51.110 --> 38:54.040
who also happens to know
about her past relationship

38:54.040 --> 38:57.080
with an ex-boyfriend,
among other things.

38:57.080 --> 38:59.040
These are things
you tell someone

38:59.040 --> 39:02.100
you have a personal
relationship with,

39:02.100 --> 39:07.080
however brief,
not an attacker.

39:07.080 --> 39:09.220
Something doesn't fit.

39:18.080 --> 39:21.030
- I'm sorry.
- You tried.

39:21.030 --> 39:25.030
Should I appeal?

39:25.030 --> 39:26.160
- Sit.

39:30.020 --> 39:32.000
We could appeal,

39:32.000 --> 39:34.120
but I don't think we'd win.

39:34.120 --> 39:37.030
You're not in what we call
a suspect class,

39:37.030 --> 39:39.120
and there's no special
protection for people with--

39:39.120 --> 39:41.020
- Funny faces.

39:44.110 --> 39:45.210
So you're not recommending

39:45.210 --> 39:47.210
that we keep going
with this case?

39:49.120 --> 39:50.140
- No.

39:54.040 --> 39:57.180
- Well, thank you for your time,
Ms. Washington.

39:59.200 --> 40:02.140
- I wish I could have been
more help.

40:02.140 --> 40:05.140
- Well, I appreciate
you not laughing, anyway.

40:05.140 --> 40:08.150
Good day.

40:08.150 --> 40:10.040
- Good-bye, Mr. Pyle.

40:21.110 --> 40:23.070
- Between
all the back and forth,

40:23.070 --> 40:24.190
the one piece of evidence

40:24.190 --> 40:28.190
that stands out most
is that you didn't try.

40:28.190 --> 40:31.000
The boy was arrested.

40:31.000 --> 40:32.160
Court papers were filed.

40:32.160 --> 40:34.100
The fact that you didn't
first try,

40:34.100 --> 40:36.140
Ms. Young,
to work something out,

40:36.140 --> 40:39.140
that tells me that you were
leading with fear and anger,

40:39.140 --> 40:41.180
not necessarily
Kendall's interests.

40:41.180 --> 40:43.130
- That isn't true.

40:43.130 --> 40:45.060
- Well, I'm not satisfied

40:45.060 --> 40:47.200
that you've exhausted
every possible remedy.

40:47.200 --> 40:51.020
Taking away a boy's father,
that's severe enough

40:51.020 --> 40:54.080
not to be
the first course of action.

40:54.080 --> 40:57.120
So I'm ordering you both
to try again.

40:57.120 --> 41:00.110
If you fail, try again.

41:00.110 --> 41:03.040
Then, maybe, come to me.

41:03.040 --> 41:06.190
Mr. Young, I am tempted
to restrain your son

41:06.190 --> 41:09.180
from coming to your office,
but I'm not there yet.

41:09.180 --> 41:11.140
We seem to have
two intelligent

41:11.140 --> 41:13.110
and loving parents here,

41:13.110 --> 41:17.040
so let's put some of that
intelligence and love to work.

41:17.040 --> 41:20.040
For God's sake,
this is not about you.

41:20.040 --> 41:23.200
This is about your son.

41:23.200 --> 41:26.210
The petition
to modify custody is denied.

41:26.210 --> 41:34.190
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:41.200 --> 41:43.180
- Will the defendant
please rise.

41:47.230 --> 41:50.130
Madam Foreperson,
the jury has reached a verdict?

41:50.130 --> 41:53.070
- We have, Your Honor.

41:53.070 --> 41:55.170
Commonwealth
versus Randy Strunk,

41:55.170 --> 41:58.140
on the charge
of assault and confinement,

41:58.140 --> 42:02.090
for the purpose of stealing
a motor vehicle while armed,

42:02.090 --> 42:07.160
we find the defendant,
Randy Strunk, guilty.

42:09.180 --> 42:12.050
- The jury is dismissed
with the thanks of the court.

42:12.050 --> 42:13.180
We're adjourned.

42:13.180 --> 42:19.160
<i>♪ ♪</i>

42:19.160 --> 42:21.120
- Good job.
Thank you.

42:21.120 --> 42:24.110
- Thank you.

42:24.110 --> 42:32.090
<i>♪ ♪</i>

42:33.130 --> 42:35.070
- Let's go.

43:03.020 --> 43:05.120
- He ready?

43:05.120 --> 43:07.020
- Not quite.

43:07.020 --> 43:09.000
- I'll wait.

43:26.070 --> 43:28.200
- Hey, Dad.
- Hey.

43:28.200 --> 43:31.050
- Just be a couple minutes.

43:31.050 --> 43:33.230
All right, almost done.

43:35.120 --> 43:37.170
How many tablespoons of water
does it take

43:37.170 --> 43:41.020
to fill a gallon container
3/4 full?

43:41.020 --> 43:43.230
- Who'd use a tablespoon
to fill a gallon container?

43:43.230 --> 43:45.140
- Somebody with
too much time on his hands.

43:45.140 --> 43:47.140
How many tablespoons
equal an ounce?

43:47.140 --> 43:49.140
- Two.
- Okay, figure it out.

43:49.140 --> 43:53.050
<i>♪ ♪</i>

43:53.050 --> 43:56.200
- 192.
- Good.

43:56.200 --> 43:58.100
Last one.

43:58.100 --> 44:01.220
This is conversion
from feet to meters.

44:01.220 --> 44:04.110
- Oh, man.
- Never mind.

44:04.110 --> 44:05.170
You go to Europe someday,

44:05.170 --> 44:06.170
and somebody
asks you a question.

44:06.170 --> 44:08.070
Answer in feet,

44:08.070 --> 44:09.190
they'll look at you
like you're crazy.

44:09.190 --> 44:11.050
- 'Cause it'll be
Paris, France,

44:11.050 --> 44:12.160
and I'm talking English.

44:12.160 --> 44:14.160
- Never mind,
let's just do it.

44:14.160 --> 44:22.140
<i>♪ ♪</i>
